data.content:
## What breaks

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider allowed synchronous LINQ by opting in to sync-over-async (e.g., `CosmosOptionsExtension` with `EnableSyncOverAsync`). **In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed.** Synchronous query and save operations on the Cosmos provider now throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

Every call in your repository is affected:

| Sync (throws in .NET 11) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(...)` | `.FirstAsync(...)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

## How to fix

Convert the repository to async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `async Task<T>` return types replace synchronous returns.
- Callers must be updated to `await` these methods (async propagates up the call stack).
- Remove the old `EnableSyncOverAsync` configuration — it's no longer recognized.
- The relational providers (SQL Server, PostgreSQL, etc.) still support sync operations; this is Cosmos-specific.
